Recent advances in machine learning have shown that classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are capable of achieving high accuracy on image recognition tasks. However, these models are typically quite large and require a lot of computational resources to train. In this paper, we introduce a new type of CNN, called a quantum convolutional neural network (QCNN), which uses quantum principles to reduce the input size of an image by a factor of two. This allows us to train our model more efficiently and achieve state-of-the-art performance on a variety of image datasets. We also discuss the results of our experiments and provide an analysis of why data augmentation did not improve the performance of our model.
